Pages are left unusable when their content contains invalid XML characters. Users are left with a message similar to the following: {code}Error: The XML content could not be parsed. There is a problem at line 1, column 19991. Parser message: String ']]>' not allowed in textual content, except as the end marker of CDATA section at [row,col {unknown-source}]: [1,19991]{code}

It would be good to provide the user with a way of fixing the page (without having to directly modify the content in their database). In the words of a customer:
{quote}
before passing the data to the XML parser to be parsed, you should check for these invalid chars (which are guaranteed to crash the parser) and either filter them out (since they're bad data anyway) or expand them into ASCII strings like "\u0019" and let the user edit them out of their docs. There is no good reason the user should ever receive that error message stating the data in the database is unparsable XML.
{quote}

